    "It is Anscombe, Ford (2018, p.6) notes, who gives this \"third conception of human agency\" its \"clearest expression\" in Twentieth Century action theory.",
    "Second, even if these arguments go wrong, and a version of the standard story can be told that allows for extended cognitive agency, it would need to be explained why the degree of agential extension allowed by the modified standard story coincided with the degree required by the action theoretic argument for HEC.",
    "Since the account Davidson gives of the rationally normative dimension of agency ends at the point of causal output from brain to world, too neat an unexplained coincidence between the causal bounds of action and the bounds of extended cognitive agency would make this solution look unacceptably ad hoc.",
    "But, we might worry, isn't the Anscombean solution also ad hoc?",
    "This brings us to our third consideration, to be developed below."
